# Approved slide templates

## General rule

- Every new slide must be based on one of the approved templates below.
- Do not create unique layout patterns for each new slide.
- Reuse these templates consistently across the deck.

## Approved templates

### 1. Title slide

- Main use: opening slide.
- Typical structure: title, optional subtitle, optional small meta line.
- Visual role: establishes the deck style.

### 2. Section slide

- Main use: transition between large parts of the talk.
- Prefer a short phrase or heading.
- `.shout` is preferred when appropriate.

### 3. Simple list slide

- Main use: 3-6 concise bullets.
- Structure: heading + list.
- `.next` can be used for progressive reveal.

### 4. Simple text slide

- Main use: short explanation without a bullet list.
- Structure: heading + one short paragraph or 2-3 compact text blocks.
- Use this as a fallback instead of inventing a custom layout.

### 5. Centered image slide

- Main use: image as the main content.
- Variants:
  - with heading above;
  - without heading.
- Default behavior: image is placed inside the existing slide structure, not as a full-screen background.

### 6. Fullscreen image slide

- Main use: strong visual slide.
- Variants:
  - image only;
  - image with overlay heading.
- Use only when the image should dominate the slide.

## Template selection

- If the user asks for a new slide and does not specify a type, pick the closest matching approved template.
- If two templates seem equally valid, ask which one to use.
- Do not mix multiple templates into a new hybrid layout unless explicitly requested.

## Consistency rules

- Keep spacing, heading placement, and image treatment consistent across slides of the same template type.
- A new slide should feel like another instance of an existing system, not a new design experiment.
